Cue: Excuse me, do you understand English?
I don’t know where it is.
Where do you want to eat? (informal)
I don’t want to eat here.
What do you want to eat? (informal)
Do you want to eat something?  (informal)
Don’t you want to eat anything?
I don’t know where the bathroom is.
No sé dónde está el baño.
What do you want to drink?
I want to drink a soda.
How much money do you have? (informal)
How much time do you have? (informal)
All right, but I’m going to pay.
Bueno, pero yo voy a pagar.
Why are you going to pay?  (informal)
I like to buy good things.
Is it OK if I pay?
You’re not going to drink anything? (informal)
If there is no time, I don’t eat.
Si no hay tiempo, no como.
At what time do you eat? (informal)
The coffee here is very good.
El café aquí es muy bueno.
Can you pay for them? (informal, f)
I can have a coffee now.
I drink a lot of coffee.
Are you going to drink it?
All right, you can speak it.
In an hour and a half.
I don’t want to talk now.
Do you want to have a coffee?
Who are you going to eat with?
Who’s going to pay for it?
How much time do you (pl.) have?
He doesn’t want to eat alone.
He also is going with us.
My wife wants to eat with us.
Mi esposa quiere comer con nosotros.
We want to pay for them.
We have a lot of friends here.
How many people are there here?
How many people do you have?
My wife right now is ready.
Are you leaving in one week?
At one o’clock in the afternoon.
A la una de la tarde.
When is he going to be here?
How long is he going to be there?
I don’t know who this man is.
No sé quién es este hombre.
How long are you going to be there?
Give me a cup of tea.
There are two women over there.
I want a cup of tea.
She drinks tea when she is sick.
Toma el té cuándo está enferma.
Do you know a good doctor?
I think that I have it.
Write it down for me, please.
I don’t understand when you say it.
I need a glass of water.
Do you think that it’s close by?
Do you think that it’s far?
What is the name of the street?
I’m going to write it down. (m)
When are you going to go?
I’m going to go with you.
It doesn’t matter if it’s today or tomorrow.
No importa si es hoy o mañana.
I don’t need to write it down. (f)
Where do you want to go?
Does your father live with you?
Let’s go to see a film.
Come to his house with me.
A la casa de mi padre.
I go a lot to the movies.
I have not seen him today.
Is your father at home now?
That film is excellent for learning Spanish.
Esa película es excelente para aprender español.
We have spoken Spanish at home.
You have not seen them at our house?
¿No los has visto en nuestra casa?
I haven’t seen them in a long time.
No los he visto en mucho tiempo.
I prefer to go with you.
I can help you with your English. (formal)
Tal vez un café con leche.
Are you going to go there?
We’re going together to the theatre.
